      <hedline>
        <hl1>Busting Crime, or Just Eardrums?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kenneth A Bruffee letter contrasts new anticrime system on Upper East Side with recorded message he got when he called 911 to report break-in on block in Park Slope, Brooklyn (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I'm glad the Upper East Side is getting a neat key-chain-operated anticrime system (''On Unmean Street, Thumbs Will Work as Crime Busters,'' front page, Sept. 13). In my Park Slope neighborhood, things are different. One early morning last week I was doing my exercises, and I looked out the window and I saw a man jimmying a car door. I called 911 and got a recording.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I'm glad the Upper East Side is getting a neat key-chain-operated anticrime system (''On Unmean Street, Thumbs Will Work as Crime Busters,'' front page, Sept. 13). In my Park Slope neighborhood, things are different. One early morning last week I was doing my exercises, and I looked out the window and I saw a man jimmying a car door. I called 911 and got a recording.</p>
        <p>The thief soon gave up on the lock and smashed the car window, so I called my local precinct, five blocks away, and suggested that it send a car. The nice man took my name and phone number. Had I called 911? I had, I replied, but should I try again? Don't bother, he said, that's what we do ourselves. Do the officers get a recording, too?</p>
        <p>As I hung up the phone, the thief pedaled jauntily away on his bike.</p>
        <p>KENNETH A. BRUFFEE  Brooklyn, Sept. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
